              <h2>How this sand calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Sand is usually sold by volume (cubic yards or cubic meters), by
                weight (tons or tonnes), or in pre‑packed bags. This calculator
                converts your project dimensions into all three so you can
                compare quotes and order the right amount.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Calculate the volume of sand</h3>
              <p>The basic idea is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Volume</strong> = Area × Depth</p>
              </div>
              <p>The calculator supports three common shapes:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Rectangle / square</strong>: \( \text{Area} =
                  \text{length} \times \text{width} \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Circle</strong>: \( \text{Area} = \pi \times
                  \left(\dfrac{\text{diameter}}{2}\right)^2 \)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Ring / border</strong>: \( \text{Area} = \text{outer
                  area} - \text{inner area} \)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                All dimensions are converted internally to feet (imperial) or
                meters (metric), then multiplied to get volume in cubic feet or
                cubic meters. From there we convert to:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>cubic yards (1 yd³ = 27 ft³)</li>
                <li>cubic meters (1 m³ ≈ 35.3147 ft³)</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>2. Convert volume of sand to weight</h3>
              <p>
                To estimate weight, we multiply the volume by the sand density
                you choose. Typical values are:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Dry loose sand</strong>: ~100 lb/ft³ (≈ 1600 kg/m³)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Compacted or wet sand</strong>: 110–120 lb/ft³ (≈
                  1760–1920 kg/m³)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Weight</strong> = Volume × Density</p>
                <p>Example (imperial):</p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Weight (lb)} = \text{Volume (ft³)} \times
                  \text{Density (lb/ft³)}\)
                </p>
                <p>
                  \(\text{Weight (short tons)} = \dfrac{\text{Weight
                  (lb)}}{2000}\)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                In metric, the calculator uses kg/m³ and converts to kilograms
                and metric tonnes (1 tonne = 1000 kg).
              </p>

              <h3>3. Estimate number of sand bags</h3>
              <p>
                If you enter a bag weight, the tool estimates how many bags you
                need:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Number of bags</strong> = Total weight ÷ Bag weight
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                For example, if you need 2,700 lb of sand and you buy 50 lb
                bags: \( 2700 \div 50 = 54 \) bags.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Waste and compaction allowance</h3>
              <p>
                Sand settles and compacts, and some is always lost during
                handling. The
                <strong>waste &amp; compaction</strong> field increases your
                calculated volume by a percentage:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Adjusted volume</strong> = Volume × (1 + Waste% / 100)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Typical allowances:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>5–10% for small, well‑measured projects</li>
                <li>10–15% for larger areas, uneven ground, or deep fill</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Worked example</h2>
              <p>
                Suppose you’re laying pavers on a
                <strong>12 ft × 10 ft</strong> patio with a
                <strong>2 in</strong> sand bed, using typical dry sand at 100
                lb/ft³ and a 10% waste allowance.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>Convert depth: 2 in = 2 ÷ 12 = 0.167 ft</li>
                <li>Area: 12 × 10 = 120 ft²</li>
                <li>Volume (no waste): 120 × 0.167 ≈ 20 ft³</li>
                <li>Adjusted volume (10%): 20 × 1.10 = 22 ft³</li>
                <li>Cubic yards: 22 ÷ 27 ≈ 0.81 yd³</li>
                <li>Weight: 22 × 100 = 2,200 lb ≈ 1.1 short tons</li>
                <li>50 lb bags: 2,200 ÷ 50 = 44 bags</li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The calculator performs all of these steps instantly and shows
                the results in both imperial and metric units.
              </p>

              <h2>Typical sand depths for common projects</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Paver bedding layer</strong>: 1–2 in (2.5–5 cm) over a
                  compacted base
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sandbox for small children</strong>: 4–6 in (10–15 cm)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Sandbox for older kids / digging</strong>: 8–12 in
                  (20–30 cm)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Leveling low spots / general fill</strong>: varies,
                  often 6–12 in (15–30 cm)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Always check local building codes and manufacturer
                recommendations for pavers, playgrounds, or structural fill.
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How do I calculate how much sand I need?</h3>
              <p>
                Measure the length and width of the area, choose a compacted
                depth, and convert everything to the same units. Multiply length
                × width × depth to get volume, then convert to cubic yards or
                cubic meters. Finally, multiply by the sand density to get
                weight, or divide by the volume per bag to get the number of
                bags. This calculator automates all of these steps.
              </p>

              <h3>How many tons of sand are in a cubic yard?</h3>
              <p>
                With typical dry sand at about 1.35 tons per cubic yard (2,700
                lb/yd³), 1 yd³ ≈ 1.3–1.5 short tons depending on moisture and
                compaction. If your supplier gives a different density, enter it
                in the density field for a more accurate estimate.
              </p>

              <h3>How many 50 lb bags of sand are in a cubic yard?</h3>
              <p>
                One cubic yard is 27 cubic feet. A 50 lb bag of dry sand is
                roughly 0.5 ft³, so you need about 54 bags per cubic yard (27 ÷
                0.5). The calculator uses your chosen density and bag weight to
                compute this automatically.
              </p>

              <h3>What type of sand should I use?</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pavers</strong>: concrete sand or coarse bedding sand
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Playground / sandbox</strong>: washed play sand, free
                  of sharp particles
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Mortar / masonry</strong>: masonry sand with
                  appropriate gradation
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>General fill</strong>: local fill sand, often mixed
                  with fines
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The calculator does not distinguish types, but density can vary
                slightly between them, so adjust if you have a value from your
                supplier.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I order extra sand?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. It’s better to have a small surplus than to run short. A
                5–15% allowance is common. Use the
                <strong>waste &amp; compaction</strong> field to build this
                safety margin into your estimate.
              </p>
